---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'coverage-comparison', text: 'Coverage Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'pricing', text: 'Pricing', level: 2 },
  { id: 'network-and-claims', text: 'Network and Claims', level: 2 },
  { id: 'who-should-choose', text: 'Who Should Choose Which', level: 2 },
  { id: 'verdict', text: 'Our Verdict', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Aetna International Review', href: '/providers/aetna-international' },
  { title: 'GeoBlue Review', href: '/providers/geoblue' },
  { title: 'Best US Expat Insurance', href: '/best/expat-health-insurance' },
];

const coverageColumns = [
  { key: 'feature', header: 'Feature' },
  { key: 'aetna', header: 'Aetna International' },
  { key: 'geoblue', header: 'GeoBlue' },
];

const coverageRows = [
  { feature: 'US Network', aetna: 'Aetna (1.7M+ providers)', geoblue: 'Blue Cross (largest US)' },
  { feature: 'Maximum Coverage', aetna: '$1M-$5M', geoblue: '$1M-$5M' },
  { feature: 'Inpatient Care', aetna: true, geoblue: true },
  { feature: 'Outpatient Care', aetna: 'Prime/Platinum', geoblue: 'Choice/Excel' },
  { feature: 'Mental Health', aetna: true, geoblue: 'Choice/Excel' },
  { feature: 'Maternity', aetna: 'Optional', geoblue: 'Excel tier' },
  { feature: 'Medical Evacuation', aetna: 'Up to $1M', geoblue: 'Up to $500K' },
  { feature: 'Telehealth', aetna: 'Select plans', geoblue: 'Included' },
  { feature: 'US Coverage', aetna: 'Integrated', geoblue: 'Integrated' },
];

const pricingColumns = [
  { key: 'profile', header: 'Profile' },
  { key: 'aetna', header: 'Aetna Pioneer Prime' },
  { key: 'geoblue', header: 'GeoBlue Voyager Choice' },
];

const pricingRows = [
  { profile: 'Age 30, incl. US', aetna: '$250-340/mo', geoblue: '$250-320/mo' },
  { profile: 'Age 40, incl. US', aetna: '$320-440/mo', geoblue: '$320-420/mo' },
  { profile: 'Age 50, incl. US', aetna: '$450-620/mo', geoblue: '$450-580/mo' },
  { profile: 'Age 60, incl. US', aetna: '$600-800/mo', geoblue: '$620-800/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Aetna International vs GeoBlue"
  description="Compare Aetna International and GeoBlue for US expats. Both offer integrated US network access—see how they differ on coverage, price, and service."
  headline="Aetna International vs GeoBlue: US Expat Insurance Compared"
  subheadline="Two excellent options for Americans abroad who need seamless US healthcare access. Here's how they stack up."
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Quotes from Both"
  ctaButtonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
  <p>
    If you're an American living abroad and need insurance that works seamlessly in both the US and internationally, Aetna International and GeoBlue are the two leading options. Both offer what most international insurers can't: integrated access to major US healthcare networks.
  </p>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Aetna International</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>Part of CVS Health / Aetna</li>
        <li>Access to 1.7M+ US providers</li>
        <li>Pioneer (tiered) and Navigator (modular) plans</li>
        <li>Strong employer/corporate options</li>
        <li>London-based international operations</li>
        <li>24/7 multilingual support</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">GeoBlue</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>Blue Cross Blue Shield's international arm</li>
        <li>Full BCBS US network (largest in US)</li>
        <li>Voyager (long-term) and Trekker (travel) plans</li>
        <li>Familiar to most Americans</li>
        <li>Pennsylvania-based operations</li>
        <li>Strong mobile app with provider finder</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">The US Coverage Advantage</h3>
    <p class="text-blue-800">
      Both Aetna International and GeoBlue include US coverage as a core feature, not an expensive add-on. With other international insurers like Cigna or Allianz, adding US coverage can increase premiums by 40-60%. Aetna and GeoBlue are built for Americans who need to use healthcare in both locations.
    </p>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Both Providers"
    description="Get quotes from Aetna International and GeoBlue."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="coverage-comparison">Coverage Comparison</h2>
  <p>
    Both providers offer comprehensive coverage. The differences are in plan structures and specific benefits.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={coverageColumns} rows={coverageRows} />
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>Key differences:</strong>
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>GeoBlue connects to the Blue Cross network—the largest in the US with 96% of hospitals</li>
    <li>Aetna's Navigator plans offer modular customization; GeoBlue uses fixed tiers</li>
    <li>Aetna has higher medical evacuation limits ($1M vs $500K)</li>
    <li>GeoBlue includes telehealth; Aetna offers it on select plans</li>
    <li>Both exclude pre-existing conditions similarly (2-year lookback typical)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Plan Structure Differences</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Aetna</strong> offers two product lines:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pioneer:</strong> Tiered plans (Pioneer, Prime, Platinum) with increasing benefits</li>
    <li><strong>Navigator:</strong> Modular plans where you select coverage modules (outpatient, dental, maternity, etc.)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <strong>GeoBlue</strong> uses a simpler structure:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Voyager:</strong> Essential, Choice, and Excel tiers for long-term expats</li>
    <li><strong>Trekker:</strong> Travel medical insurance for shorter trips</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="pricing">Pricing</h2>
  <p>
    Pricing is similar between these two providers. The main variable is which benefits you need—both offer ways to reduce premiums through deductibles and plan selection.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={pricingColumns} rows={pricingRows} />
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>Notes on pricing:</strong>
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Both include US coverage in base pricing—no expensive add-on</li>
    <li>Deductible options range from $0 to $5,000 for both</li>
    <li>Higher deductibles can reduce premiums by 20-30%</li>
    <li>GeoBlue's Essential tier is 25-35% cheaper than Choice</li>
    <li>Aetna's Navigator (modular) can be cheaper if you don't need all benefits</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Get Your Actual Price"
    description="Pricing varies by age, plan, and deductible. Get a personalized quote."
    buttonText="Get a Quote"
    buttonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
  />

  <h2 id="network-and-claims">Network and Claims</h2>

  <h3>US Network Access</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>GeoBlue</strong> provides access to the Blue Cross Blue Shield network—the largest in the US. Over 100 million Americans use BCBS domestically, and 96% of US hospitals are in-network. If you've had BCBS before, you'll find the same network abroad.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Aetna International</strong> connects to Aetna's US network of 1.7 million+ providers. While slightly smaller than BCBS, Aetna's network covers all major markets and includes most top hospitals and specialists.
  </p>

  <h3>International Network</h3>
  <p>
    Both providers maintain extensive international networks:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>GeoBlue:</strong> 1.7 million+ contracted providers in 190 countries</li>
    <li><strong>Aetna:</strong> 1.7 million+ providers globally, with CVS Health backing</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Claims Process</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>GeoBlue:</strong> Mobile app with photo submission, real-time tracking, and digital ID cards. Claims typically process in 7-14 days. US Blue Cross claims process faster due to existing infrastructure.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Aetna:</strong> Online portal, mobile app, and email submission. Claims typically process in 5-10 days. Direct billing available at network providers in both US and international locations.
  </p>

  <h3>Customer Service</h3>
  <p>
    Both offer 24/7 support with multilingual assistance. GeoBlue's mobile app is particularly well-reviewed for finding nearby providers. Aetna offers dedicated case managers for complex medical situations.
  </p>

  <h2 id="who-should-choose">Who Should Choose Which</h2>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Choose Aetna International If:</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>You want modular, customizable coverage</li>
        <li>You work for a US company with international assignments</li>
        <li>You need higher evacuation limits ($1M)</li>
        <li>You prefer Aetna's network over BCBS</li>
        <li>You want to pick specific benefits à la carte</li>
        <li>CVS Health backing matters for financial stability</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Choose GeoBlue If:</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>You want the largest US network (BCBS)</li>
        <li>You're already familiar with Blue Cross</li>
        <li>You prefer straightforward tiered plans</li>
        <li>Mobile app quality matters to you</li>
        <li>You want integrated telehealth</li>
        <li>Brand familiarity and trust are important</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="verdict">Our Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Aetna International and GeoBlue are both excellent choices for US expats. The right choice depends on your preferences more than objective superiority.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>GeoBlue</strong> is the natural choice if you've used Blue Cross before and want that continuity. The BCBS network is marginally larger, and the brand is familiar to most Americans. Their tiered plans are simple to understand.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Aetna International</strong> is better if you want more customization. The Navigator modular plans let you build exactly the coverage you need without paying for benefits you won't use. The higher evacuation limits and CVS Health backing are also advantages.
  </p>
  <p>
    Both include US coverage without the premium increase you'd see with Cigna or Allianz. For Americans who split time between the US and abroad—or who might repatriate eventually—either option eliminates the coverage gap that would otherwise exist.
  </p>
  <p>
    Get quotes from both to compare actual pricing for your situation. The costs are similar enough that small differences in benefits or network preference should drive your decision.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Decide?"
    description="Compare quotes from both providers based on your specific needs."
    buttonText="Compare Plans Now"
    buttonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This comparison is for informational purposes only. Prices, coverage, and plan details change. We are not insurance brokers. Verify all information with the providers before purchasing.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
